         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne botanic &amp; zoolog. Garden, ¶ 16 May 1859. ¶ Venerable friend and colleague. ¶  ¶ You will justly regard me as very remiss in my correspondence for having not answered long before this your ve...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">59.05.16d</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Decaisne</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Bibliothèque de l'Institut de France, Paris.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne botanic &amp; zoolog. Garden,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">16 May 1859.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Venerable friend and colleague.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will justly regard me as very remiss in my correspondence for having not answered long before this your very kind letter dated 16 June 1858.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found.</p>
               </note> I have now also to acknowledge the receipt of your very friendly communication dated february 1859.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Soon after the receipt of the first of these two letters, I communicated with a "squatter" resident in the <name key="Corypha">Corypha</name> country, to send me as many seeds of the palm as possible. He accordingly sent an aboriginal to the stately groves of these trees and procured a large quantity, but as the distance where these palms grow is 300 miles from Melbourne and partially through a very wild country, it happened that the parcel was unfortunately lost on its way to me. However I will bear your request in regard to the palm fruits in mind at the next season, when they are obtainable.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Nothing gives me greater pleasure, than to aid so distinguished a botanist as yourself wherever it lays in my humble power, and I have therefore sent by this months overland mail via South hampton (freight paid) all the rarer cucurbitaceae<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The collection did not arrive; see M to J. Descaine, 25 December 1861.</p>
               </note> which I have in my collection, likewise the seeds of same &amp; also fragments of several <name key="Asclepiadeae">Asclepiadeae</name>, which I believe will prove partially new. I can only regret, that the small collection, which I forward is so little worthy of your acceptance, but it must be born in mind, that the specimens collected during Mr Gregorys expedition<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">North Australia Exploring Expedition, 1855-6.</p>
               </note> had to be carried for thousands of miles on pack horses, thus being subject to continuous braekage. After my return I did not like to make further use of the permission, given by Her Brittanic Majestys Home Government of retaining for myself a set, than laying small fragments for my herbarium aside. These I have gladly shared with you, and as I have added notes of some of the <name key="Cucurbitaceae">Cucurbitaceae</name> drawn up on the spot from fresh specimens, I still hope that they will be useful for your monograph. However better specimens of most you will find in Sir W. Hookers collection at Kew. Would you be so very kind to give publicity to my notes on <name key="Cucurbitaceae">Cucurbitaceae</name> after you kindfully corrected the interim-names?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I feel under great obligation to you for your prompt information on <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Arauja">Arauja</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Araujia</seg>?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg> &amp; <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Rhyncharrhena">Rhyncharrhena</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>. The latter I have published in the 5. No. of my Fragmenta phytographiae Australiae where also a new species of Cucumis (<name key="Cucumis%20jucunda">Cucumis jucunda</name>) with edible fruits is described.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See B59.13.02, p. 45.</p>
               </note> I believe you are quite correct in referring <name key="Cucurbita%20micrantha">Cucurbita micrantha</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See B55.13.03, p. 17.</p>
               </note> to Cucumis.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Arauja">Arauja</name> must have been thrown on shore of East Australia with ballast or by other means [like]<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS damaged.</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Soliva%20anthemoides">Soliva anthemoides</name>,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Soliva anthemifolia</seg>?</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Helosciadium%20leptophyllum">Helosciadium leptophyllum</name>, <name key="Tagetes%20glandulifera">Tagetes glandulifera</name>, <name key="Centratherum%20muticum">Centratherum muticum</name> (<name key="Centaurea%20riparia">Centaurea riparia</name>, All. Cunn &amp; DC. prod.) and many other South American plants.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will be aware that <name key="Lagenaria%20vulgaris">Lagenaria vulgaris</name> &amp; <name key="Sicyos%20angulatus">Sicyos angulatus</name> grow also indigenously in Australia.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Corypha%20Australia">Corypha Australia</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">C. australis</seg>?</p>
               </note> occurs as far South as 37° 30' in Gipps Land, as stated in my annual report 1854.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B55.11.01.</p>
               </note> It seems that the letter of Count Tascher you refer to in regard to <name key="Josephinia">Josephinia</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
               </note> must have been lost.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With the best wishes for your welfare I remain, venerable friend,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Your very obliged</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I find that the length of the funicle gives good characters of discrimination in some of the <name key="Cucurbitaceae">Cucurbitaceae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation: 'M. Ferdinand Müller'.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
